A '''Power Surge''' is an unexpected, temporary, uncontrolled increase in current or voltage in an electrical circuit. While they can occur in any size circuit, power surges are mostly discussed in relation to large-scale electricity delivery (community-sized or larger power grids). In environments where components of the power grid are older or less-well-mainained, power surges (and drop-offs or [[power outage|brown outs]]) are more frequent and noticeable, however in more stable power supplies, observable power surges are infrequent.

Occasional power surges are unavoidable in large-scale electricicity delivery, however there are many mechanisms in place to mitigate damage and inconvenience during electrical transmission and consumption. At the consumption end, [[Fuse (electrical)|Fuses]] and [[circuit breaker]]s were invented to protect devices using electricity by 'breaking' or interrupting the flow of electricity when it reaches a critical threshhold. Unfortunately, the critical threshold for sensitive electronic devices (notably computer equipment) can be much lower, necessitating the use of auxiliary [[surge protector]]s, whose purpose is to moderate the flow of electricity within a much narrower spectrum in order to prevent the damage that a power surge or temporary drop-off could cause.

